# Editing W source

- Indent with **tabs** (spaces are a compiler warning) and keep a trailing
  newline. Blocks open with `:`, no semicolons, `#` comments.
- `|`/`&` are bitwise and never short-circuit; use `&&`/`||` for guards.
  A hex literal with bit 31 set sign-extends into the word-sized `int` on
  every target (`0xffffffff` is `-1` even on x64 — build 32-bit masks at
  runtime, see `lib/sha256.w`). `byte` is a built-in 1-byte type name;
  don't use it as an identifier (`byte = 5` parses as a declaration).
- After editing, check the file without producing a binary:
  `./bin/wv2 check --json <file>` (add `x64` after `--json` for the 64-bit
  target). Exit 0 with empty stdout means clean. A `postToolUse` hook
  (`.cursor/hooks.json`) also runs this check automatically after every
  `.w` edit and injects the diagnostics — treat that feedback as
  authoritative and fix it before moving on.
- Fix warnings, not just errors: the self-host build stages compile with
  `--strict`, so any warning fails `./wbuild build`.
- Pick focused tests with `./bin/wtest changed <file>` (build it with
  `./wbuild wtest`) instead of guessing or running the full suite first.
- Look up where a symbol is declared with
  `./bin/wv2 symbols --json <file>` rather than grepping when the file
  compiles.
